[ distant clatter ]

13:06.739 --> 13:09.243
VERONICA: You think
construction sites have security?

13:09.243 --> 13:12.458
‐ My family had a construction business.
Trust me, we're fine.

13:12.458 --> 13:14.212
‐ Ah.
‐ Mm.

13:14.212 --> 13:15.507
What were we talking about?

13:15.507 --> 13:18.513
‐ Uh‐‐ Um... men suck.

13:18.513 --> 13:20.809
‐ Ah. Yes.

13:20.809 --> 13:22.228
Some. [ clears throat ]

13:22.228 --> 13:24.273
Many.

13:24.273 --> 13:26.402
Aaron Heller, who called me
the C‐word

13:26.402 --> 13:29.450
because I canceled plans with him
the day my mum died.

13:31.037 --> 13:33.375
Sam Hicks, who said I completed him

13:33.375 --> 13:35.713
and then completed
in my roommate's mouth.

13:37.592 --> 13:39.930
The asshole who raped me

13:39.930 --> 13:43.353
and every other asshole
who's put his hands and his mouth

13:43.353 --> 13:44.982
and his dick where it didn't belong.

13:48.865 --> 13:50.117
Your turn.

13:53.123 --> 13:56.922
‐ Find every last scrap of dirt
on that lying piece of shit!

13:56.922 --> 13:59.093
‐ Penn's a punk,
no argument there.

13:59.845 --> 14:02.266
‐ I want to know every girl
who ever laughed in his face.

14:02.266 --> 14:04.855
Every sweat sock
he ever tried to impregnate.

14:04.855 --> 14:06.609
Every back zit he ever popped.

14:06.609 --> 14:09.405
‐ But you'll just end up making this
into a bigger thing than‐‐

14:09.405 --> 14:11.326
‐ What, <i>I'm</i> makin' it a bigger thing?!

14:11.326 --> 14:13.163
He stood up in front of the City Council!

14:13.163 --> 14:15.042
‐ But Clyde, no one believes him!

14:15.042 --> 14:17.505
He's the pizza boy who cried wolf!

14:17.505 --> 14:21.220
And if I've learned anything from hip hop,
you don't punch down.

14:21.220 --> 14:22.389
‐ I‐‐

14:23.475 --> 14:25.647
You listen to hip hop?
‐ No.

14:25.647 --> 14:28.193
But Veronica dragged me
to <i>Straight Outta Compton.</i>

14:28.193 --> 14:30.030
I‐I feel I'm up to speed.

14:30.030 --> 14:31.157
‐ [ chuckles ]

14:32.911 --> 14:35.207
‐ Come on.
‐ [ sighs ]

14:35.207 --> 14:36.710
‐ You all right?

14:37.378 --> 14:38.839
‐ Yeah.

14:38.839 --> 14:41.971
Sorry, this kind of shit
just really sets me off, ya know?

14:41.971 --> 14:45.812
I mean, I've worked very hard to get back
some semblance of respectability.

14:46.772 --> 14:49.402
‐ [ sighs ]

14:49.402 --> 14:51.030
CLYDE: And it's not like I don't get it.
I get it.

14:51.030 --> 14:53.034
I mean, I've done some things
I'm not proud of.

14:53.034 --> 14:54.245
‐ Haven't we all?

14:54.245 --> 14:56.457
CLYDE: Well, we haven't all
robbed multiple banks.

14:56.457 --> 14:58.336
KEITH: Not for lack of trying.
CLYDE: Yeah.

14:58.336 --> 15:01.092
But I do feel like shootin' something,
though. You wanna join me?

15:01.092 --> 15:04.683
‐ Promise there'll be beer?
CLYDE: Scout's honor.

15:04.683 --> 15:05.977
See you at noon.

15:07.021 --> 15:08.189
‐ Oh, my God,

15:08.189 --> 15:10.862
oh, my God, oh, my God.

15:10.862 --> 15:12.741
Have you thought
about what you're gonna wear?

15:12.741 --> 15:16.122
I'm thinking a backless top,
but with jeans, just to balance it out.

15:16.122 --> 15:18.711
‐ I was thinkin' trench coat,
nothing underneath.

15:18.711 --> 15:20.380
‐ Ooh, the old standby.

15:20.380 --> 15:23.596
And where is your gentleman caller
taking you tomorrow, Dad?

15:23.596 --> 15:26.100
‐ Duck hunting.
‐ Kinky.

15:26.727 --> 15:29.608
You realize it's not gonna be
in a carnival booth?

15:30.985 --> 15:32.362
‐ Gives me a chance to work him.

15:32.362 --> 15:36.454
‐ You and our prime suspect, drunk,
in a secluded wood with guns.

15:36.454 --> 15:38.416
What could go wrong?
‐ That's the spirit.

15:39.544 --> 15:42.801
‐ Any luck tying him and Big Dick
to those shell companies?

15:42.801 --> 15:44.721
You were bragging about
your mad computer skills.

15:44.721 --> 15:47.519
‐ No, I meant "bad" computer skills.

15:47.519 --> 15:49.606
The list is on my computer.
Have at it.

15:50.817 --> 15:53.614
Still feel like we're on
the right track here?

15:53.614 --> 15:55.283
‐ I do.

15:55.283 --> 15:56.954
‐ Lay it out for me.

15:58.541 --> 16:00.293
‐ [ clears throat ]

16:00.293 --> 16:02.966
Big Dick wants to remake
the boardwalk on a budget,

16:02.966 --> 16:07.725
so he enlists his Chino pal, Clyde,
to soften up the market.

16:07.725 --> 16:12.192
The harassment campaign isn't driving
local business owners out fast enough,

16:12.192 --> 16:16.325
so they commission a bunch of bombs
from their other Chino pal, Perry Walsh.

16:16.325 --> 16:18.539
We get close to Walsh, they...

16:20.375 --> 16:22.797
And they still have some bombs,

16:22.797 --> 16:24.175
so they just keep going.

16:25.260 --> 16:28.559
‐ I can almost get there. It's just...

16:28.559 --> 16:30.437
the collar bomb.

16:30.437 --> 16:32.942
Maybe Big Dick and Clyde would kill
to get what they want,

16:32.942 --> 16:35.238
but this collar bomb,

16:35.238 --> 16:39.873
the person who does that feels like
someone just released from Arkham Asylum.

16:39.873 --> 16:41.752
<i>[ phone chimes ]</i>

16:59.078 --> 17:02.376
So this is what it would have been like
if you had friends in high school.

17:06.969 --> 17:07.971
‐ [ snorts ]

17:07.971 --> 17:09.516
‐ What?

17:09.516 --> 17:12.647
‐ The former owner of Comrade Quacks
just asked Nicole for a favor.

17:13.774 --> 17:16.989
‐ Why is that funny?
‐ She sued the guy.

17:16.989 --> 17:19.869
Took the only thing he owned.
Comrade Quacks.

17:19.869 --> 17:21.707
‐ Sued him over what?

17:21.707 --> 17:24.336
‐ Um, not providing adequate security.

17:24.336 --> 17:26.424
‐ She was raped?

17:28.428 --> 17:31.058
‐ I didn't say th‐‐
KEITH: Nightclub is a sizeable settlement,

17:31.058 --> 17:32.729
I can tell she wasn't murdered...

17:33.772 --> 17:36.570
...and you said it was over security.

17:36.570 --> 17:39.074
‐ You should be
a private investigator.

17:39.074 --> 17:40.536
Why are you so fired up?

17:40.536 --> 17:42.874
‐ I was looking for patterns
among the victims.

17:42.874 --> 17:44.502
Have you noticed
that each of the bombs

17:44.502 --> 17:47.049
killed someone with a sex offense
in his history?

17:47.049 --> 17:49.888
Jimmy Hatfield, at the Sea Sprite,
kicked out of his first college

17:49.888 --> 17:52.644
after two women accused him
of popping up in their dorm room beds

17:52.644 --> 17:54.564
naked and uninvited.

17:54.564 --> 17:57.486
Perry Walsh. Mailed an ex‐girlfriend
a package bomb

17:57.486 --> 18:00.660
along with a misogyny‐laced
"get well soon" card.

18:00.660 --> 18:03.832
Bryce Linden, accused earlier
of trying to roofie women,

18:03.832 --> 18:06.546
and you told me
that the margarita slinger on the beach

18:06.546 --> 18:08.257
said something sexual to you.

18:08.257 --> 18:10.428
It's a pattern. But I was missing a perp.

18:10.428 --> 18:12.684
‐ And now?
‐ What about Nicole?

18:12.684 --> 18:14.395
‐ As the perp?!
‐ I'm just sayin'.

18:14.395 --> 18:16.983
We saw what she did to Jimmy Hatfield.

18:16.983 --> 18:19.363
Not a lot of ladies slip on sap gloves

18:19.363 --> 18:22.202
and knock men out
with practiced right hooks.

18:22.202 --> 18:23.997
Plus we know for sure
that almost every victim

18:23.997 --> 18:25.876
passed through Quacks.

18:27.254 --> 18:29.676
‐ This is a cussing joke, right?

18:29.676 --> 18:33.141
I make fun of you for befriending
our lead suspect,

18:33.141 --> 18:35.855
and now you pull this theory
out of your ass.

18:35.855 --> 18:38.694
‐ Yeah. Yeah, I'm probably
grasping at straws.

18:38.694 --> 18:41.157
She hasn't spoken about
her expertise with explosives,

18:41.157 --> 18:42.451
has she?
‐ Oh, yeah.

18:42.451 --> 18:45.916
She makes those perfectly round bombs
like Boris and Natasha.

18:45.916 --> 18:47.169
And she likes to‐‐

18:49.173 --> 18:50.383
‐ What?

18:50.383 --> 18:54.141
‐ Her family is... in construction,
which means...

18:54.141 --> 18:56.521
‐ Demolition. She has the know‐how.

18:57.397 --> 18:58.984
‐ But answer this.

18:59.861 --> 19:03.409
Nicole's business hinges on spring break.

19:03.409 --> 19:05.581
Why would she destroy her livelihood?

19:07.083 --> 19:09.881
‐ [ sighs ] Fair enough.

19:09.881 --> 19:10.925
‐ Point, set, match.

19:10.925 --> 19:13.639
<i>My</i> new friend is not a mass murderer.

19:13.639 --> 19:15.810
Yours probably is.

19:17.730 --> 19:18.857
‐ We'll see.

19:23.659 --> 19:25.161
‐ Chief.

19:25.161 --> 19:26.873
Things just got weirder.

19:26.873 --> 19:28.292
‐ What's that?

19:28.292 --> 19:30.296
‐ It's a note from someone
claiming to be the bomber.

19:30.296 --> 19:32.050
‐ Let me see that.

19:32.050 --> 19:34.429
‐ Y'know, you should probably
wear gloves.

19:34.429 --> 19:36.350
I can just read it to you.

19:36.350 --> 19:38.981
"I am the Neptune spring break bomber.

19:38.981 --> 19:42.530
I hope you and your feeble‐minded officers

19:42.530 --> 19:45.578
have enjoyed my first four explosions.

19:45.578 --> 19:50.128
But now the real fun begins,
unless you accede to my demands."

19:50.128 --> 19:53.510
And there's...
an ultimatum for the mayor.

19:53.510 --> 19:55.848
MARCIA: Let me see that.
‐ And something about Neptune

19:55.848 --> 19:57.810
prostituting itself each year.

20:02.904 --> 20:04.824
‐ Has anybody else seen this?

20:04.824 --> 20:06.327
VERONICA:
Yeah, I'm coming home now.

20:06.327 --> 20:08.707
Do you want me
to pick something up for dinner?

20:08.707 --> 20:10.251
[ snorts ] Like really cooking?

20:10.251 --> 20:12.088
Or opening cans of soup?
[ knock at door ]

20:14.426 --> 20:16.514
Maybe you should handle dinner.

20:16.514 --> 20:19.604
Nope, a recidivist. Be back soon.

20:19.604 --> 20:20.606
Weevil?

20:23.946 --> 20:26.116
[ Weevil sighs ]

20:26.116 --> 20:27.870
‐ What's wrong with you, Veronica?

20:30.083 --> 20:32.420
‐ You know, there are
a range of opinions.

20:33.422 --> 20:36.513
‐ You got a problem with me,
deal with me.

20:38.517 --> 20:40.729
‐ What you talkin' 'bout, Weevil?

20:40.729 --> 20:44.194
‐ Using a 19‐year‐old kid as a chip.

20:44.194 --> 20:46.992
Wow. That's some gutter shit.

20:46.992 --> 20:48.285
[ sniffs ]

20:48.285 --> 20:51.125
Try remembering when you were cool.

20:51.125 --> 20:54.047
‐ Hm. Well, I mean,
since you asked so nicely.

20:55.718 --> 20:57.847
WEEVIL:
Juan Diego's brother?

20:57.847 --> 21:02.648
He took out two high‐ranking
<i>Nuestra Familia</i> street commanders.

21:02.648 --> 21:05.738
That kid shows up
in the Cali prison system,

21:05.738 --> 21:08.075
they're gonna put him in a box.

21:08.075 --> 21:11.415
‐ Oh, <i>that</i> Juan Diego.
The ice machine shitter.

21:11.415 --> 21:16.843
Well, maybe he should have considered that
before he held a knife to my throat.

21:16.843 --> 21:18.471
But you know what?

21:20.475 --> 21:21.477
Bygones.

21:23.732 --> 21:26.236
Now, if you'll just... fill me in

21:26.236 --> 21:30.286
on what's causing the uptick
in petty crime by the boardwalk,

21:30.286 --> 21:32.958
my heart will remain
three sizes too big.

21:33.835 --> 21:37.217
‐ [ exhales ] No clue.

21:37.217 --> 21:38.720
‐ Bullshit!

21:40.891 --> 21:43.270
‐ You and me.

21:43.270 --> 21:44.857
We were close once.

21:46.193 --> 21:48.405
If there's anything left‐‐
‐ There's not.

21:49.659 --> 21:51.955
My dad went out on a limb for you.

21:52.790 --> 21:54.752
He and Cliff spent a year

21:54.752 --> 21:57.006
building your case
against the Sheriff's Department,

21:57.006 --> 21:58.510
and you settled behind their backs.

21:58.510 --> 22:01.014
‐ I had a wife and a daughter
to think about.

22:02.350 --> 22:05.106
I don't live on Cherry Tree Lane, V!
‐ [ scoffs ]

22:05.106 --> 22:07.068
‐ I needed the money!

22:07.068 --> 22:08.780
Does that make me a criminal?

22:08.780 --> 22:11.118
‐ No. Being a criminal
makes you a criminal.

22:12.370 --> 22:16.295
Which is why Jade split town, right?
She didn't want her kid raised by a‐‐

22:16.295 --> 22:17.923
‐ Stop there, Veronica!

22:21.931 --> 22:23.518
<i>[ phone rings ]</i>

22:24.896 --> 22:26.566
Hector.

22:26.566 --> 22:27.943
Yeah. Go ahead.

22:28.904 --> 22:30.406
Are you sure?

22:32.953 --> 22:35.584
That's great news. All right.

22:35.584 --> 22:36.586
Yeah, bye.

22:38.005 --> 22:39.967
‐ Great news, huh?

22:39.967 --> 22:42.013
Did you make the cover
of <i>Hoodlum Weekly?</i>

22:43.224 --> 22:46.898
‐ Cops can't find the guy who filed
the complaint against Juan Diego.

22:46.898 --> 22:48.944
He must've split town.

22:48.944 --> 22:52.367
‐ So the charges are dropped!
How about that?

22:52.367 --> 22:54.914
Turns out I'm <i>not</i> lowdown gutter trash.

22:56.793 --> 22:58.254
‐ Jury's out.

23:06.854 --> 23:08.148
‐ [ sighs ]

23:14.620 --> 23:17.125
CAROL:
The primary font he used is Avenir.

23:17.125 --> 23:19.170
‐ <i>Which is French for "future."</i>

23:19.964 --> 23:21.801
<i>Is he maybe indicating time frame?</i>

23:21.801 --> 23:25.308
‐ Avenir's also classified
as a geometric typeface.

23:25.308 --> 23:28.188
‐ I'll start drawing squares, triangles,
and trapezoids through the text.

23:28.188 --> 23:30.109
Maybe there's a message.

23:30.109 --> 23:32.781
‐ <i>The word "fun" is blue.</i>

23:32.781 --> 23:35.871
<i>"House" is red.</i>
<i>Red and blue make purple.</i>

23:35.871 --> 23:37.791
<i>Purple funhouse.</i>

23:37.791 --> 23:41.632
<i>The funhouse version...</i>
<i>of purple is green.</i>

23:43.636 --> 23:46.976
<i>The next bomb won't be at the beach,</i>
<i>it'll be somewhere green.</i>

23:46.976 --> 23:49.314
<i>A‐A field, a wooded area,</i>
<i>someone's lawn.</i>

23:49.314 --> 23:52.278
‐ Yeah, well, that narrows it down
to literally everywhere.

23:52.278 --> 23:55.493
And the funhouse version of purple
is green? What?!

23:55.493 --> 23:56.913
‐ <i>What's your better idea?</i>

23:56.913 --> 23:59.877
‐ Uh, you know what,
it's not better than funhouse purple.

23:59.877 --> 24:02.048
But you've set the bar so high, Don.

24:02.048 --> 24:04.595
‐ <i>You're still stuck on</i>
<i>your Big Dick theory, Penn?</i>

24:05.972 --> 24:07.058
<i>Why?</i>

24:07.058 --> 24:10.147
‐ The $250,000 reward?

24:10.147 --> 24:13.738
I mean, I understand
I'm not independently wealthy

24:13.738 --> 24:17.788
like the rest of you, so by all means,
keep following Don down the garden path.

24:17.788 --> 24:20.126
<i>‐ Think about it, Penn.</i>

24:20.126 --> 24:22.589
<i>Does this note really sound like Big Dick?</i>

24:22.589 --> 24:25.261
‐ Did it ever occur to you
that it could be fake?

24:25.261 --> 24:27.098
Big Dick or Clyde Pickett

24:27.098 --> 24:28.977
could have written it
to throw us off the scent!

24:28.977 --> 24:32.358
‐ <i>Everyone hold on to your straws.</i>
<i>Someone's grasping for them.</i>

24:33.444 --> 24:35.866
‐ You know what?
[ tapping keyboard ]

24:35.866 --> 24:37.619
DON:
<i>Are you changing my filter again?</i>

24:37.619 --> 24:38.872
‐ [ laughter ]

24:38.872 --> 24:41.001
‐ <i>Did he change it?</i>
<i>What did he make me?</i>

24:42.253 --> 24:43.882
MARCIA:
Look, it may sound absurd‐‐

24:43.882 --> 24:46.094
‐ You're shitting me. It's bullshit.

24:46.094 --> 24:50.436
It's some dumb kid from Hearst College
thinking he's funny.

24:50.436 --> 24:51.814
‐ Well, maybe.

24:51.814 --> 24:54.152
But if there's even
a five percent chance, Mark‐‐

24:54.152 --> 24:56.908
‐ No, I say that we roll the dice.
I'm not doing this.

24:56.908 --> 24:59.120
‐ Way to stake out
the moral high ground, Mark.

24:59.120 --> 25:01.124
‐ Well, eat shit, Marcia!

25:01.124 --> 25:03.462
Theresa, will you talk some sense
into her?

25:04.422 --> 25:06.218
‐ Mark, I agree with Chief Langdon.

25:06.218 --> 25:08.515
From a human standpoint,

25:08.515 --> 25:11.812
and not to be crass,
but from a political standpoint as well,

25:11.812 --> 25:14.359
I don't see where you have much choice.

25:16.822 --> 25:18.283
‐ [ sighs ]

25:20.329 --> 25:21.916
I need to call my wife.

25:23.878 --> 25:25.715
‐ You'd do it if you were mayor.

25:26.717 --> 25:28.888
You're a natural‐born hero.

25:28.888 --> 25:30.182
KEITH:
Debatable.

25:30.182 --> 25:31.184
[ tapping keyboard ]

25:31.184 --> 25:33.940
You buyin' that letter?
It reeks of knucklehead.

25:33.940 --> 25:35.359
‐ Agreed.

25:35.359 --> 25:38.575
I guess we'll know if,
as the letter promises,

25:38.575 --> 25:41.706
"the real fun is only just beginning."

25:41.706 --> 25:44.920
‐ Hey, you fare any better than I did
on those shell companies?

25:44.920 --> 25:46.382
VERONICA:
Nope.

25:46.382 --> 25:48.928
We're gonna need someone
with serious hacking chops.

25:48.928 --> 25:51.391
‐ I thought you youngsters
were all computer whizzes.

25:51.391 --> 25:53.605
What happened?
Too busy taking selfies?

25:53.605 --> 25:55.190
‐ Hey, are you cooking something?

25:55.190 --> 25:56.944
‐ Nope.

25:56.944 --> 25:58.656
‐ You sure you're not cooking anything?

26:00.367 --> 26:01.996
[ fire crackling ]

26:01.996 --> 26:03.123
Holy shit!

26:09.762 --> 26:10.972
Ohh.

26:18.529 --> 26:21.619
Your breakfast burrito, I presume?

26:21.619 --> 26:25.000
‐ Yeah. I heated up the toaster
and I forgot to put it in.

26:26.837 --> 26:29.968
‐ Maybe if we just hook up jumper cables
to your brain every morning?

26:30.970 --> 26:33.058
[ Veronica muttering ]

26:33.058 --> 26:35.145
[ water running ]

26:41.826 --> 26:43.120
What is goin' on with you?

26:43.120 --> 26:44.330
[ knocking ]
MATTY: Hello?

26:44.330 --> 26:46.376
Anybody there? It's Matty.

26:49.633 --> 26:52.889
So I... thought I should drop by

26:52.889 --> 26:54.893
and, um, apologize.

26:54.893 --> 26:56.647
‐ For?

26:56.647 --> 26:58.651
‐ I told Penn your theory...

26:58.651 --> 27:01.699
about all the criminal activity
being sourced back to Chino.

27:03.201 --> 27:06.542
I didn't think he'd go broadcasting it‐‐
KEITH: It's okay.

27:06.542 --> 27:10.592
I knew a girl your age who frequently
made ill‐advised decisions.

27:10.592 --> 27:12.094
‐ Who?
‐ Hm?

27:12.094 --> 27:13.931
‐ I just wanna be able to help.

27:13.931 --> 27:15.309
‐ How are your hacking skills?

27:15.309 --> 27:17.062
‐ Non‐existent.

27:17.062 --> 27:19.610
‐ Oh, cuss a duck.

27:19.610 --> 27:22.281
‐ I do know someone, though.
He's amazing.

27:22.281 --> 27:24.912
You guys read about how
everyone at Neptune High

27:24.912 --> 27:26.331
got straight A's last year?

27:26.331 --> 27:28.628
‐ Yeah. That was him?
‐ Mm‐hm.

27:28.628 --> 27:30.172
‐ Wow. He's a friend of yours?

27:30.172 --> 27:31.759
‐ Um, not really.

27:31.759 --> 27:33.513
‐ Hm. That's too bad.

27:33.513 --> 27:35.725
‐ I think he likes me, though.

27:39.775 --> 27:41.319
[ school bell ringing ]

27:41.319 --> 27:42.906
GIRL: Hey there.
WALLACE: Hey, good morning. Thank you.

27:42.906 --> 27:45.202
BOY: Hey.
WALLACE: Good morning. Good morning.

27:45.202 --> 27:47.707
Hey. Matty. Have you seen Caelen?

27:47.707 --> 27:51.047
‐ Uh, he had to talk to Ms. Adler.
He should be here soon.

27:51.966 --> 27:54.053
‐ So, you excited?
‐ About?

27:54.053 --> 27:56.182
‐ San Diego Air & Space Museum!

27:56.182 --> 27:58.563
It's the Curtiss B‐1 Robin
of field trips!

27:58.563 --> 28:01.150
‐ Is that a plane?

28:01.150 --> 28:03.113
‐ Yes. That's a plane.

28:03.739 --> 28:05.994
‐ [ students chattering ]
WALLACE: Listen up.

28:05.994 --> 28:09.375
We only have a few hours
at the museum, and a lot to see.

28:09.375 --> 28:11.714
So I need you all on best behavior.

28:11.714 --> 28:14.553
And just a reminder,
I'm still waiting on computing programs

28:14.553 --> 28:17.057
from our optics unit from some of you.

28:17.057 --> 28:19.103
You hear that last part, Owen?

28:19.103 --> 28:20.648
I know the work's below your level‐‐

28:20.648 --> 28:23.779
‐ A kid in diapers could write
a scratch version of Pong, Coach Fennel.

28:23.779 --> 28:26.451
‐ I have a kid in diapers.
I'll test your theory.

28:26.451 --> 28:28.371
I still need you to turn it in.

28:29.206 --> 28:31.210
‐ [ students murmuring ]

28:32.505 --> 28:34.258
[ tapping keyboard ]

28:40.187 --> 28:42.232
‐ He doesn't get it.

28:42.232 --> 28:44.028
No one at this school does.

28:44.028 --> 28:48.078
"Get your assignments done,
move through the maze..."

28:48.078 --> 28:52.252
It's like, who cares
that you've got this...

28:52.252 --> 28:54.173
giant brain in there?

28:55.175 --> 28:56.929
Hey...

28:56.929 --> 28:58.264
weird question.

28:59.058 --> 29:01.312
Do you know anything
about real estate?

29:03.149 --> 29:04.611
‐ Sorry.

29:04.611 --> 29:07.449
‐ Ohh. That's too bad.

29:07.449 --> 29:10.122
I have all these people coming at me
to buy my dad's motel,

29:10.122 --> 29:11.542
and I wanna pick the right one,

29:11.542 --> 29:14.380
but I'm having an impossible time
getting info on the companies.

29:16.092 --> 29:19.390
I'm rambling. Sorry to bug you.

29:19.390 --> 29:20.768
‐ Wait, hold on.

29:22.396 --> 29:24.024
You can hack their systems.

29:25.193 --> 29:28.283
‐ I'm sure these places
have insane security.

29:28.283 --> 29:30.872
I'd have to be... a computer genius.

29:33.126 --> 29:34.755
‐ <i>You</i> wouldn't have to be.

29:37.384 --> 29:39.514
‐ Oh, my God, Owen.

29:39.514 --> 29:41.017
That's so sweet.

29:43.062 --> 29:45.150
‐ [ quietly ] It's a slippery slope, Owen.

29:45.150 --> 29:47.864
‐ While my client did have relations

29:47.864 --> 29:51.830
with the man in question,
no money changed hands.

29:51.830 --> 29:53.166
JUDGE: Really.

29:53.166 --> 29:55.505
‐ The john was fresh from a tour
in Afghanistan,

29:55.505 --> 29:59.053
and Ms. Carlyle has
a "veterans fly free" policy.

29:59.053 --> 30:02.685
My client has saluted many vets.

30:02.685 --> 30:03.854
Men, women,

30:03.854 --> 30:07.361
from both Iraq wars, Vietnam, Korea‐‐

30:07.361 --> 30:10.033
even an intrepid World War II vet.

30:10.033 --> 30:12.914
They really are
the Greatest Generation.

30:12.914 --> 30:16.295
Now, I'm perfectly willing
to trot out every last one of them,

30:16.295 --> 30:20.345
but wouldn't it be better
to applaud Ms. Carlyle's love of country

30:20.345 --> 30:23.393
rather than putting us all
through a lengthy trial?

30:24.478 --> 30:26.859
JUDGE: [ sighs ]
Motion for dismissal granted.

30:26.859 --> 30:28.361
[ strikes gavel ]

30:28.361 --> 30:30.156
Ms. Carlyle, you're free to go.

30:30.156 --> 30:32.662
‐ Thank you, Your Honor.
And God bless America.

30:36.628 --> 30:39.843
‐ See, that's what I've been saying.
Taking a knee <i>is</i> patriotic.

30:39.843 --> 30:41.847
‐ Hello, Veronica.

30:41.847 --> 30:44.936
Oh. What can I do for you?

30:44.936 --> 30:47.650
‐ Juan Diego De La Cruz.
I believe he's a client of yours?

30:47.650 --> 30:50.155
‐ Only for another couple hours.
Charges have been dropped.

30:50.155 --> 30:51.575
That one's in the win column.

30:51.575 --> 30:53.202
‐ New charges were just filed
against him.

30:53.202 --> 30:55.206
‐ Well, shit.
‐ By me.

30:55.206 --> 30:58.379
‐ If I could be so bold‐‐
‐ I need leverage over Weevil.

30:59.214 --> 31:00.593
‐ Begging the question...

31:00.593 --> 31:03.264
‐ Weevil may not have
anything to do with the bombs,

31:03.264 --> 31:06.897
but I think he has information that could
get us closer to knowing who does.

31:07.899 --> 31:11.280
Juan Diego is scheduled
to be re‐arraigned this afternoon.

31:11.280 --> 31:15.246
‐ Hm. I'd planned on taking The Missus
on a hike this afternoon.

31:15.246 --> 31:16.792
The Missus is my new puppy.

31:16.792 --> 31:18.252
‐ You named your dog The Missus?

31:18.252 --> 31:20.173
‐ Says the owner of a dog named Pony.

31:20.173 --> 31:22.427
‐ Okay.
CLIFF: So, Weevil...

31:22.427 --> 31:25.058
ah, can't be happy
about any of this, I take it.

31:25.058 --> 31:28.231
‐ I guarantee it.
‐ Well, then, The Missus will understand.

31:28.231 --> 31:29.651
VERONICA:
Oh, one more thing.

31:29.651 --> 31:33.993
Middle‐aged white guys share secrets
with others of their kind, don't they?

31:33.993 --> 31:35.286
‐ How else would we know

31:35.286 --> 31:38.042
which no‐prescription‐needed websites
selling Viagra are legit?

31:38.042 --> 31:42.259
‐ Gross. Um, has my dad
talked to you about... memory issues?

31:42.259 --> 31:43.428
‐ I forget.

31:44.054 --> 31:45.348
VERONICA:
Cliff.

31:46.100 --> 31:47.227
Cliff!

31:47.227 --> 31:50.776
Have you noticed anything unusual
with my dad?

31:50.776 --> 31:52.989
With his memory?
‐ Unusual?

31:52.989 --> 31:56.788
‐ You cagey mothercusser.
Tell me what you know.

31:56.788 --> 32:00.253
‐ It is not my place to say, Veronica.
Ask your dad.

32:00.880 --> 32:04.637
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I have a new old client I need to see.

32:09.438 --> 32:11.568
‐ I‐I don't think I can do this.

32:11.568 --> 32:14.156
‐ Of <i>course</i> you can.
You are the bravest man I know.

32:14.156 --> 32:17.997
‐ My dad is going to see. All our friends.
What'll they think?

32:17.997 --> 32:20.210
‐ They'll think what everyone else
in town is going to think:

32:20.210 --> 32:22.297
that Mark Dobbins is a hero.

32:22.297 --> 32:24.594
‐ [ sighs ] Yeah?
What about your sister?

32:24.594 --> 32:25.721
She won't think I'm a hero.

32:25.721 --> 32:27.140
‐ My sister's a bitch.

32:27.140 --> 32:29.896
‐ [ both laugh ]
‐ Come here.

32:29.896 --> 32:32.025
I'm so proud of you.

32:32.025 --> 32:33.654
DOBBINS: Ahh,
I shoulda worked out more.

32:33.654 --> 32:36.408
‐ You look great. Come on.

32:38.496 --> 32:40.083
‐ [ crowd cheering ]
PAMELA: Oh, um‐‐

32:40.083 --> 32:41.418
what about your shoes?

32:41.418 --> 32:43.172
The letter said "not a stitch."

32:43.172 --> 32:46.011
‐ I‐I‐I can't run without shoes.

32:46.011 --> 32:48.684
I think... this humiliation was the point.

32:48.684 --> 32:50.145
‐ I'm sure you're right.

32:50.145 --> 32:51.940
‐ [ crowd wolf‐whistling ]

32:53.944 --> 32:54.988
PAMELA:
Go get 'em.

32:54.988 --> 32:57.869
‐ [ breathing heavily ]

32:57.869 --> 33:00.498
‐ [ crowd cheering, applauding ]

33:00.498 --> 33:02.879
DOBBINS: Okay...
[ camera shutters clicking ]

33:02.879 --> 33:04.799
‐ [ cheering continues ]

33:07.930 --> 33:10.393
‐ You hear Santino and Tomas
were gunned down?

33:10.393 --> 33:12.565
‐ What's that, nine more dead now?

33:12.565 --> 33:14.484
Just since we've been here?

33:16.531 --> 33:17.825
‐ [ smacks lips ]

33:17.825 --> 33:18.994
Try this.

33:19.996 --> 33:22.167
‐ It's got lavender?
Like the flower?

33:22.167 --> 33:23.712
‐ Just a hint.

33:31.185 --> 33:32.855
‐ That's good!
‐ Yeah.

33:32.855 --> 33:34.358
DODIE:
That's <i>really</i> good!

33:35.068 --> 33:36.696
A lavender latte?

33:36.696 --> 33:38.742
<i>¿Por favor?</i>
SERVER: Sure.

33:38.742 --> 33:41.748
‐ Could you imaging
having a meal like this back home?

33:41.748 --> 33:45.004
Without lookin' over your shoulder
every second...

33:45.004 --> 33:47.092
afraid you'll be shot in the back?

33:47.092 --> 33:50.056
‐ But for fate,
we coulda been born here.

33:50.056 --> 33:51.977
This coulda been our lives.

33:52.937 --> 33:54.106
So normal.

33:56.820 --> 33:58.740
‐ To normal.
‐ To normal.

33:58.740 --> 34:00.159
[ Dodie chuckles ]

34:00.159 --> 34:02.163
‐ [ crowd cheering,
car horns honking ]

34:06.297 --> 34:07.883
[ horn honks ]

34:11.223 --> 34:13.854
[ crowd cheering ]

34:23.582 --> 34:25.919
‐ You know me, Veronica.
What do I always say?

34:28.132 --> 34:29.468
‐ "Are you gonna eat that?"

34:29.468 --> 34:34.937
‐ Please. I always say,
"You don't negotiate with terrorists."

34:34.937 --> 34:36.733
‐ I don't think
I've heard you say that once

34:36.733 --> 34:38.486
in the 25 years I've known you.

34:38.486 --> 34:40.949
‐ Regardless, watching our valiant mayor

34:40.949 --> 34:43.371
trotting down Ocean Ave
in his altogether

34:43.371 --> 34:45.333
was pretty damn entertaining.

34:45.333 --> 34:47.337
[ laughing ] Here it is.

34:47.337 --> 34:49.466
‐ Wait, <i>that's</i> the video
you want to show me?

34:49.466 --> 34:50.719
The naked mayor one?

34:50.719 --> 34:52.389
No. That poor man.

34:52.389 --> 34:55.813
‐ Poor man? Oh, obviously,
you haven't seen the video.

34:55.813 --> 34:57.608
He's a human tripod.

34:57.608 --> 34:59.529
It's like watching <i>The War of the Worlds.</i>

35:01.115 --> 35:04.496
Oh. Here's one of The Missus
being humped by Smoky Joe,

35:04.496 --> 35:06.500
the neighborhood Lothario.

35:06.500 --> 35:08.588
‐ Counselor? Your client?

35:08.588 --> 35:10.383
‐ Thanks, Deputy.

35:12.220 --> 35:13.515
‐ Who are you?

35:13.515 --> 35:15.894
‐ I'm your court‐appointed lawyer.
Cliff McCorm‐‐

35:15.894 --> 35:18.525
‐ Whatever.
Why is she here?

35:19.484 --> 35:20.821
‐ She's your accuser.

35:20.821 --> 35:22.449
‐ Since when?
I thought I was getting out.

35:22.449 --> 35:24.829
‐ Since this morning.
Stay strong, J.D.

35:24.829 --> 35:26.039
‐ Oh, lady, come on!

35:26.039 --> 35:28.377
‐ "Lady"? Cuss you.

35:28.377 --> 35:29.797
"Lady."

35:34.139 --> 35:36.143
‐ You have no idea
what you're doing here.

35:36.143 --> 35:38.272
‐ I'm pretty sure I do.

35:40.276 --> 35:43.533
I'm putting you
in an impossible situation.

35:43.533 --> 35:47.457
If you don't give me satisfactory answers
to my questions,

35:47.457 --> 35:50.547
I have the power to put you in Chino
where people are waiting to kill you.

35:50.547 --> 35:53.512
‐ And if I tell you what you wanna know,
I'm just as dead.

35:58.772 --> 36:00.943
‐ Where'd this money come from?

36:00.943 --> 36:02.988
‐ My wallet. You stole 'em.

36:04.575 --> 36:06.328
‐ How did <i>you</i> get 'em?

36:06.328 --> 36:08.415
‐ I own a casino.

36:09.794 --> 36:11.213
‐ Okay. I'm done here.

36:11.213 --> 36:13.510
Where's the D.A.'s office again?

36:13.510 --> 36:15.639
I just wanna
stop by and let 'em know

36:15.639 --> 36:18.770
how terrified I was when your client
held a knife to my throat.

36:18.770 --> 36:20.858
‐ You don't care that you're going
to end up getting me killed?

36:20.858 --> 36:22.277
‐ You don't seem to care about

36:22.277 --> 36:24.281
all those people
getting killed by bombs.

36:24.281 --> 36:26.703
‐ Bombs? I have
nothing to do with bombs.

36:26.703 --> 36:28.247
‐ I am not so sure.

36:29.917 --> 36:31.295
Six hundred.

36:32.548 --> 36:35.386
I mean, it's not a fortune,
but it'll get you far away from here.

36:35.386 --> 36:36.973
Talk to me and it's yours.

36:55.009 --> 36:56.638
‐ Weevil.

36:56.638 --> 36:59.142
He gave us a yard for
every spring breaker's wallet we took.

37:02.106 --> 37:04.654
‐ You ever see Weevil with this guy?

37:04.654 --> 37:08.035
‐ Lots of folks need body work done.
I can't keep track of 'em all.

37:08.035 --> 37:12.001
‐ I'd prefer you don't die,
but that's all it is, a preference.

37:18.305 --> 37:19.684
‐ Yeah, I saw him, okay?

37:19.684 --> 37:21.771
That's the money man.
Clyde something.

37:21.771 --> 37:23.190
He'd drop by Weevil's shop,

37:23.190 --> 37:25.988
and when we saw him
I knew it was payday.

37:26.906 --> 37:29.787
Weevil said that he's someone
that we don't want to mess with.

37:32.458 --> 37:35.214
SINGER: [ on radio ]
<i>♪ On the first part of the journey... ♪</i>

37:35.214 --> 37:36.759
CLYDE:
Want a beer?

37:36.759 --> 37:39.222
KEITH: Please.
SINGER: <i>♪ I was lookin' at all the life ♪</i>

37:40.559 --> 37:43.313
<i>♪ There were plants and birds</i>
<i>and rocks... ♪</i>

37:43.313 --> 37:46.654
KEITH:
That is impressive. Very impressive.

37:46.654 --> 37:48.115
‐ [ Clyde grunts ]

37:48.908 --> 37:51.956
SINGER: <i>♪ The first thing</i>
<i>I met was a fly with a buzz ♪</i>

37:51.956 --> 37:53.459
‐ Can I make a confession?

37:53.459 --> 37:55.630
SINGER:
<i>♪ ...with no clouds ♪</i>

37:55.630 --> 37:57.551
‐ I've never been hunting.

37:58.553 --> 38:00.891
‐ Coulda fooled me.
‐ [ chuckles ]

38:00.891 --> 38:03.730
‐ You've shot at <i>people,</i> though, right?
‐ I have.

38:04.690 --> 38:06.736
‐ Pretty much the same principle.
Cheers.

38:06.736 --> 38:07.738
SINGER:
<i>♪ On a horse with no name ♪</i>

38:07.738 --> 38:10.827
<i>♪ It felt good to be out of the rain ♪</i>

38:11.954 --> 38:13.708
<i>♪ In the desert... ♪</i>

38:13.708 --> 38:15.670
‐ Okay, first concert.

38:15.670 --> 38:17.465
‐ CCR. I was nine.

38:17.465 --> 38:19.260
Ended up being their final tour.

38:19.260 --> 38:21.264
‐ Wow. Weren't you Joe Cool?

38:22.726 --> 38:24.395
<i>[ cell phone rings ]</i>

38:25.439 --> 38:26.651
Ugh.

38:28.070 --> 38:29.114
Yeah?

38:30.157 --> 38:31.619
I don't care.

38:32.955 --> 38:34.792
No, I promise you, I don't.

38:34.792 --> 38:36.587
SINGER:
<i>♪ After two days... ♪</i>

38:36.587 --> 38:40.720
‐ [ sighs ] Just tell that son of a bitch
he is <i>gone.</i>

38:40.720 --> 38:43.601
If he's still there when I get back,
I'll tell him face‐to‐face,

38:43.601 --> 38:46.231
and he will <i>not</i> enjoy that encounter.

38:46.231 --> 38:48.987
SINGER:
<i>♪ I was looking at a river bed ♪</i>

38:48.987 --> 38:51.241
‐ [ sighs ] No pets.

38:52.034 --> 38:53.913
Very clear policy.

38:53.913 --> 38:56.126
This jackass renting
one of our units

38:56.126 --> 38:59.800
has a <i>boa constrictor</i>
that keeps getting loose!

38:59.800 --> 39:01.261
SINGER: <i>♪ ...the desert</i>
<i>on a horse with no name ♪</i>

39:01.261 --> 39:04.058
‐ Could come in handy
if you have an ocelot problem.

39:04.058 --> 39:05.896
‐ [ laughing ]

39:06.856 --> 39:09.737
[ grunts ] I gotta take a piss.
KEITH: Okay.

39:09.737 --> 39:13.202
SINGER: <i>♪ There ain't no one</i>
<i>for to give you no pain ♪</i>

39:13.202 --> 39:16.876
<i>♪ Da da, da,</i>
<i>da da da da da ♪</i>

39:16.876 --> 39:20.049
<i>♪ Da da da, da da ♪</i>

39:21.051 --> 39:24.767
<i>♪ Da da, da, da da da da da... ♪</i>

39:26.102 --> 39:28.106
<i>[ camera clicking ]</i>

39:30.236 --> 39:32.281
<i>[ clicking continues ]</i>

39:35.412 --> 39:36.874
[ rustling ]

39:40.005 --> 39:42.260
‐ Goddamnit. Goddamnit.

39:42.260 --> 39:45.349
What's the point of all this technology
if it doesn't work?

39:45.349 --> 39:48.188
Stupid thing isn't taking
my thumb print.

39:48.188 --> 39:50.735
‐ Well, that could be because
<i>that</i> stupid thing

39:50.735 --> 39:52.572
only takes <i>my</i> thumb print.

39:56.496 --> 39:58.458
‐ Oh, God, you see?

39:58.458 --> 40:00.672
See? I'm losing it. I'm losing‐‐

40:00.672 --> 40:02.425
[ chuckling ]

40:08.437 --> 40:12.320
So, I managed to get
some alone time with Clyde's phone.

40:12.320 --> 40:14.073
Interested in what he and Big Dick

40:14.073 --> 40:16.244
have texted each other
about the bombings?

40:17.748 --> 40:21.338
Big Dick: "There's gonna be
no Neptune left worth owning

40:21.338 --> 40:23.300
if these bombs keep going off.

40:23.300 --> 40:26.599
Not sure we have
the right police chief for the moment."

40:26.599 --> 40:31.191
Clyde responds, "At least people realize
your dead library friend isn't the guy,

40:31.191 --> 40:34.072
not after the horse collar bomb."
And it goes along like this.

40:34.072 --> 40:37.244
Just two guys trying to figure out
who they think is responsible.

40:39.123 --> 40:41.294
‐ How'd you get ahold
of Clyde's phone?

40:42.213 --> 40:44.885
‐ Clyde took a call and then left
the duck blind to relieve himself.

40:44.885 --> 40:45.970
I know what you're gonna say.

40:45.970 --> 40:48.601
‐ That he left his phone out
for you to explore?

40:49.770 --> 40:54.362
Clyde is responsible for all the shit
going down around town.

40:54.362 --> 40:57.661
He's got a‐a whole ex‐con network‐‐
‐ That's the theory.

40:57.661 --> 41:00.416
‐ It's not a theory anymore.
It's a fact.

41:00.416 --> 41:03.714
I know he's paying Weevil
to send out PCH‐ers

41:03.714 --> 41:06.386
to mug tourists
and vandalize businesses.

41:07.514 --> 41:08.975
‐ And the grocery store rats

41:08.975 --> 41:13.860
did come courtesy of an ex‐con
employed at Dobie's Sweet Release bakery.

41:13.860 --> 41:15.572
‐ <i>And</i> I think it's safe to assume

41:15.572 --> 41:18.326
that Matty was right
about the first bomb being placed

41:18.326 --> 41:20.289
in the vending machine from Alpha‐Jolly,

41:20.289 --> 41:23.838
courtesy of fellow Chino inmate
Perry Walsh.

41:23.838 --> 41:25.382
‐ [ sighs ]

41:28.305 --> 41:31.102
I see you've been digging through
my personal files.

41:31.979 --> 41:33.691
‐ Your memory journal.

41:39.870 --> 41:42.082
Were you ever gonna tell me?

41:42.709 --> 41:44.630
‐ I didn't want to scare you.

41:44.630 --> 41:46.550
‐ Well, guess what. I'm scared.

41:46.550 --> 41:48.094
‐ I'm not dying.

41:48.094 --> 41:50.432
‐ Well, that's reassuring.
KEITH: I've seen doctors.

41:50.432 --> 41:54.398
‐ Yeah, like this, um,
fancy pants in Beverly Hills?

41:56.069 --> 41:57.656
Did you take out a second mortgage?

41:57.656 --> 41:59.158
‐ Clyde got me in there.

41:59.158 --> 42:01.120
And I know what you're gonna say.

42:01.120 --> 42:03.668
I lost my perspective. And maybe
you're right. Ethically‐‐

42:03.668 --> 42:06.339
‐ Do you think I give a shit
about ethics here?

42:06.339 --> 42:10.055
If Clyde and Big Dick offer you
top‐flight medical care,

42:10.055 --> 42:11.725
you say yes. You hear me?

42:15.274 --> 42:17.444
Screw appearances.

42:20.785 --> 42:23.206
I know Keith Mars can't be bought.

42:27.298 --> 42:28.884
[ sighs ]

42:34.896 --> 42:36.399
[ Veronica sighs ]

42:40.490 --> 42:43.664
KEITH [ voice quavering ]:
I've been thinking a lot lately.

42:43.664 --> 42:46.502
Obsessing, really.
Veronica, I am afraid that

42:46.502 --> 42:49.091
I'm just gonna end up doing
something s‐stupid.

42:49.091 --> 42:50.887
‐ No.
KEITH: Somethin' dumb.

42:50.887 --> 42:52.431
Forget something. Blow a case.

42:52.431 --> 42:55.813
Or worse...
get one of us hurt.

42:57.901 --> 43:01.282
I'm starting to think that maybe
it's time to hang it up.

43:01.282 --> 43:02.827
‐ What?

43:03.579 --> 43:05.499
No. You're 56.

43:05.499 --> 43:08.421
56 is the new 19.
I can show you the article.

43:08.421 --> 43:11.595
‐ [ laughs ] 56 is 56, Veronica.

43:12.931 --> 43:14.935
‐ Once we wrap up this case...

43:16.312 --> 43:18.734
take a vacation.

43:18.734 --> 43:20.530
I'll hold down the fort.

43:20.530 --> 43:25.080
‐ [ sighs ]
Let's talk about that.

43:28.378 --> 43:30.883
VERONICA: At first, I thought
he was gonna say he was retiring,

43:30.883 --> 43:32.554
which would have been bad enough.

43:32.554 --> 43:35.308
Instead, he tells me
we should shut down the business

43:35.308 --> 43:37.731
and I should go chase waterfalls
or some shit.

43:37.731 --> 43:39.651
Does he actually think
that I would leave town

43:39.651 --> 43:41.320
after hearing news like that?

43:41.320 --> 43:43.868
"Oh, a doctor put you on medication
for dementia?

43:43.868 --> 43:45.580
Cool! See ya!"

43:49.211 --> 43:51.340
‐ Sounds like he wants you to leave.

43:51.340 --> 43:54.681
‐ He's being a martyr.
Trying to let me off the hook.

43:56.142 --> 43:59.733
‐ Because you being off the hook
will make him happy.

44:02.154 --> 44:05.160
‐ Please. I cannot deal with
Therapy Logan right now.

44:06.120 --> 44:07.874
‐ Y'know, there's this scene
in <i>The Crucible‐‐</i>

44:07.874 --> 44:10.755
‐ Oh. Broadway Logan
might not be much better.

44:10.755 --> 44:12.967
‐ Salem witch trials.

44:12.967 --> 44:17.059
This guy's dying under the weight
of these heavy stones. But...

44:18.687 --> 44:20.858
he won't give in to his tormenters.

44:22.194 --> 44:24.156
He just keeps saying, "More weight."

44:26.870 --> 44:28.164
‐ Okay, I‐‐

44:28.164 --> 44:30.252
‐ That's you, Veronica.

44:32.214 --> 44:34.719
‐ I'm a witch?
‐ You're not happy.

44:34.719 --> 44:38.017
And you act like you don't have the power
to change your circumstances.

44:39.688 --> 44:41.775
I love you. I do.

44:44.363 --> 44:46.409
But if I'm not what you want, say so.

44:48.581 --> 44:51.628
You want to stay in Neptune,
you want to leave Neptune,

44:51.628 --> 44:53.339
it's also your call.

44:53.339 --> 44:55.385
It's your life.
You get to do what you want.

44:55.385 --> 44:58.308
‐ Are you serious right now?
I <i>do</i> what I want.

44:58.308 --> 44:59.435
LOGAN:
No, you don't.

45:00.437 --> 45:01.439
Not really.

45:01.439 --> 45:03.401
‐ Ooh, you are starting to piss me off.

45:04.236 --> 45:06.825
‐ If I wasn't around
and your father wasn't around,

45:06.825 --> 45:08.494
what would you be doing?

45:08.494 --> 45:10.750
‐ I would be sticking my head in the oven,

45:10.750 --> 45:14.131
because the two most important people
in my life would be gone.

45:17.471 --> 45:18.933
‐ [ sighs ]

45:20.101 --> 45:22.941
‐ [ Veronica sobs ]
LOGAN: I'm sorry.

45:23.441 --> 45:25.738
It was the wrong time to bring this up.

45:25.738 --> 45:27.449
[ sighs ]

45:28.326 --> 45:31.082
Your dad's gonna be fine.

45:31.082 --> 45:32.543
It's all gonna be okay.

45:35.549 --> 45:37.344
‐ [ chatter ]

45:37.344 --> 45:38.597
‐ Hello.

45:39.348 --> 45:41.185
Ho ho ho ho! Look at that.

45:41.185 --> 45:42.437
She seems nice.

45:43.816 --> 45:46.613
This is the cheap shit lost‐and‐found,
isn't it?

45:46.613 --> 45:48.951
I mean, if you did find
an Egyptian heirloom ring

45:48.951 --> 45:51.372
that belonged to a congressman
that was worth hundreds of thousands,

45:51.372 --> 45:53.001
you wouldn't keep it in here,
would you?

45:53.001 --> 45:54.546
‐ That's all there is.

45:55.463 --> 45:57.426
‐ That's all there is. All right.

45:57.426 --> 45:58.804
Wonderful bedside manner.

45:58.804 --> 46:00.975
There ya are. Ha ha ha!

46:00.975 --> 46:02.729
Help me with the wind.

46:02.729 --> 46:05.400
Oh, yeah. Mm.

46:06.235 --> 46:07.112
Mm.

46:07.780 --> 46:08.866
Oh!

46:08.866 --> 46:11.287
Nicole Malloy.
Just the lady I was lookin' for.

46:11.287 --> 46:14.001
‐ Ah. Seen your face on benches.
‐ Thank you.

46:14.001 --> 46:15.588
‐ I'm on my way out.
‐ Well.

46:15.588 --> 46:17.174
Well, this'll just take a minute.

46:17.174 --> 46:18.761
Ya know, just a minute.

46:18.761 --> 46:21.600
So, from what I can suss out,

46:21.600 --> 46:24.731
all the bombing victims
spent time in your club, right?

46:24.731 --> 46:28.029
So I'm thinkin' that the killer
was pickin' his victims here.

46:28.029 --> 46:30.325
And I'm hopin' that maybe
you can let me check out

46:30.325 --> 46:32.370
the security footage
dating back to the first day

46:32.370 --> 46:34.083
that the spring breakers
came into town.

46:34.083 --> 46:36.420
‐ Why would I do that?
VINNIE: $250,000.

46:36.420 --> 46:38.592
It's a nice chunk of change, right?

46:38.592 --> 46:40.846
I certainly can be persuaded
to spring‐‐

46:42.265 --> 46:45.480
[ high‐pitched ringing ]

46:53.287 --> 46:55.416
‐ [ distant panicky chattering ]

46:59.634 --> 47:01.428
MAN:
We gotta get outta here! Let's go!

47:01.428 --> 47:03.141
‐ [ panicked voices continue ]

47:06.188 --> 47:09.236
‐ [ camera shutters clicks ]
‐ [ police radio chatter ]

47:09.236 --> 47:12.450
‐ So, prior to the blast,
did you notice anyone suspicious?

47:13.161 --> 47:16.125
‐ Yeah.
The bartender had a bad attitude.

47:16.125 --> 47:17.670
It made me uncomfortable.

47:18.505 --> 47:21.010
So, the bomb.
Men's room or ladies'?

47:21.010 --> 47:22.972
‐ I'll ask the questions, Mr. Van Lowe.

47:22.972 --> 47:24.851
‐ Call me Vinnie.

47:24.851 --> 47:26.646
SARGENT: Chief...

47:26.646 --> 47:29.318
no dead so far.
Three in critical condition.

47:30.361 --> 47:31.573
More of these nails.

47:31.573 --> 47:33.117
[ camera clicks ]
‐ <i>Muchas gracias.</i>

47:34.036 --> 47:35.539
‐ So, where were we?

47:35.539 --> 47:39.213
‐ Oh. Uh, I believe you were giving me
a list of your persons of interest?

47:39.213 --> 47:40.215
VERONICA:
Are you all right?

47:40.215 --> 47:41.718
I got here as fast as I could.
NICOLE: Thanks.

47:41.718 --> 47:44.056
‐ You: stay.

47:44.056 --> 47:47.605
This is a crime scene. No P. I. s.

47:47.605 --> 47:49.316
‐ He's a P.I.

47:49.316 --> 47:51.445
[ grunts ]
He's a witness.

47:51.445 --> 47:52.447
‐ Yeah, I'm a witness.

47:52.447 --> 47:54.451
‐ Well, Veronica's my friend...

47:54.451 --> 47:56.748
she came to comfort me
at my request.

47:56.748 --> 47:58.669
‐ Congrats, Veronica.
You found a friend.

47:58.669 --> 48:01.716
‐ Is that a woman's jacket, Vinnie?
‐ It was free.

48:01.716 --> 48:02.760
‐ I should hope so.

48:02.760 --> 48:04.597
‐ Ms. Mars? Please.

48:06.475 --> 48:07.603
[ Veronica sighs ]

48:07.603 --> 48:09.106
‐ I'll be okay.

48:09.106 --> 48:10.693
‐ We still on for tomorrow night?

48:10.693 --> 48:12.279
‐ More than ever.

48:12.279 --> 48:13.447
‐ Okay.

48:14.366 --> 48:16.120
MARCIA: All right,
I just have a couple more questions.

48:16.120 --> 48:17.540
VINNIE: Yeah,
and I have a few as well.

48:17.540 --> 48:19.334
MARCIA: Excuse me?
VINNIE: I'm sorry, you go first,

48:19.334 --> 48:22.340
and then I'll answer. I'll follow up.
I'll be the caboose.

48:24.136 --> 48:25.973
‐ [ sighs wearily ]

48:25.973 --> 48:30.566
Uh, Alexa, shuffle my playlist
After Work Tunes.

48:30.566 --> 48:33.362
ALEXA:
<i>Shuffling playlist After Work Tunes.</i>

48:33.362 --> 48:35.491
<i>[ song playing ]</i>

48:46.138 --> 48:49.436
SINGER:
<i>♪ Now I, I'm cravin' your body ♪</i>

48:49.436 --> 48:52.860
<i>♪ Is this real,</i>
<i>my temperature's risin' ♪</i>

48:52.860 --> 48:54.906
<i>♪ I don't want to feel ♪</i>

48:54.906 --> 48:56.200
<i>♪ I'm in the wrong place ♪</i>

48:56.200 --> 48:57.202
[ rapping on door ]

48:57.202 --> 48:59.039
<i>♪ To be real ♪</i>

49:00.542 --> 49:04.592
<i>♪ Whoa, and I'm longing to love you... ♪</i>

49:06.470 --> 49:07.598
‐ Oh. Carol.

49:07.598 --> 49:09.017
‐ "Prostitute yourself."

49:09.017 --> 49:10.562
‐ Uh, sorry?

49:10.562 --> 49:12.900
‐ Uh, can I come in?
‐ Yeah. Yeah.

49:16.323 --> 49:17.492
What's this about?

49:19.705 --> 49:22.545
CAROL: The bomber.
In the letter in the newspaper,

49:22.545 --> 49:25.425
he warned about Neptune
prostituting itself.

49:25.425 --> 49:26.803
‐ Well, yeah, he's late.

49:26.803 --> 49:28.682
I mean, he should've send that letter
20 years ago.

49:28.682 --> 49:30.476
‐ It's a weird phrase, isn't it?

49:30.476 --> 49:33.399
I mean, how often do you reference
prostituting yourself?

49:33.399 --> 49:35.111
‐ Uh, never.

49:35.111 --> 49:36.614
‐ Yeah! Who says that?

49:36.614 --> 49:40.246
‐ Well, weirdos and...
serial bombers, it seems.

49:40.246 --> 49:43.335
‐ Big Dick Casablancas
says it routinely.

49:43.335 --> 49:45.131
‐ W‐What? How do you know this?

49:45.131 --> 49:48.095
‐ His Twitter account.
He posts regularly.

49:48.095 --> 49:53.481
Want to know how many times he's tweeted
some variation of "prostituting yourself"

49:53.481 --> 49:54.942
since he opened his account?

49:54.942 --> 49:57.948
‐ Well, I mean, if it's more than one,
he's our guy.

49:59.034 --> 50:00.537
No!
‐ Yeah!

50:00.537 --> 50:04.169
Yeah, the fire department prostituted
itself by offering paid tours,

50:04.169 --> 50:07.801
uh, public library, same thing
for allowing the "Say Yaas" program,

50:07.801 --> 50:09.764
where drag queens
read from their journals‐‐

50:09.764 --> 50:11.935
‐ And‐‐ And‐‐ And Big Dick
is mad at the mayor, too,

50:11.935 --> 50:13.145
for delaying the NUTT vote!

50:13.145 --> 50:16.443
The bomber...
got the mayor to streak!

50:16.443 --> 50:18.155
‐ You were right, Penn!

50:18.155 --> 50:20.577
I think you were right!
PENN: [ laughing ]

50:20.577 --> 50:22.038
I was right!

50:24.084 --> 50:26.171
SINGER:
<i>♪ I'm longing to love you ♪</i>

50:26.171 --> 50:28.133
<i>♪ For one night ♪</i>

50:28.133 --> 50:29.554
<i>♪ Please let me love you ♪</i>

50:29.554 --> 50:30.471
‐ [ kiss ]

50:30.471 --> 50:32.977
SINGER:
<i>♪ With all of my might ♪</i>

50:32.977 --> 50:36.275
[ both grunting ]

50:36.275 --> 50:37.611
CAROL: I wanna take this off.
PENN: Okay.

50:37.611 --> 50:39.574
CAROL: It's so sexy that you were right.
PENN: Oh.

50:39.574 --> 50:43.080
‐ [ grunting continues ]

50:43.080 --> 50:45.126
‐ What? Oh! Oh! Did I‐‐
Did I do something wrong?

50:45.126 --> 50:48.007
‐ No, it's just there's something
digging into my back.

50:48.007 --> 50:49.009
‐ What?

50:51.848 --> 50:54.185
‐ [ screams ] Oh, my God.
‐ Oh, Jesus Christ!

50:54.185 --> 50:55.606
Jesus Christ!

50:57.066 --> 50:58.570
‐ I think it was his beak.

51:03.162 --> 51:05.207
<i>[ pop music playing over earbuds ]</i>

51:09.049 --> 51:10.468
‐ How did you know where I lived?

51:10.468 --> 51:13.808
MATTY: You had that
"No High Rises" button in your car,

51:13.808 --> 51:17.816
and the only people who give a shit
about high rises are beach people.

51:17.816 --> 51:20.029
And given your ten‐year‐old Hyundai,

51:20.029 --> 51:21.616
the place had to be rent‐controlled,

51:21.616 --> 51:24.664
limiting me to a small section
of beachfront property.

51:24.664 --> 51:26.959
And I knew you had a big dog

51:26.959 --> 51:29.799
because of the big dog toys
in said beater car.

51:30.509 --> 51:32.680
I saw a leash hangin' outside your door.

51:32.680 --> 51:34.182
[ rummaging in purse ]

51:34.182 --> 51:38.525
Anyway, my hacker acquaintance
did some digging,

51:38.525 --> 51:41.238
and it turns out
all of those out‐of‐state buyers are,

51:41.238 --> 51:46.456
in fact, shell corporations owned by
something called Phoenix Land Trust.

51:46.456 --> 51:48.127
‐ Beaver.

51:48.127 --> 51:51.801
‐ I don't know what that means,
but Phoenix Land Trust

51:51.801 --> 51:54.055
was owned by a Cassidy‐‐

51:54.055 --> 51:56.769
get this‐‐ Casablancas,

51:56.769 --> 51:59.149
‐ Mm‐hm.
‐ until his death in 2006,

51:59.149 --> 52:01.612
at which point ownership
transferred to...

52:01.612 --> 52:02.990
‐ Big Dick Casablancas.

52:02.990 --> 52:05.537
‐ His dad. Yeah.

52:05.537 --> 52:08.710
Phoenix Land Trust has bought a ton
of property in the last six months.

52:09.670 --> 52:11.716
Owen made a list of those as well.

52:13.720 --> 52:16.349
VERONICA: <i>And that's how</i>
<i>I found out my new friend Nicole</i>

52:16.349 --> 52:19.732
<i>sold Comrade Quacks</i>
<i>after the first bombing.</i>

52:19.732 --> 52:22.988
<i>Ownership was to officially transfer</i>
<i>at the end of spring break.</i>

52:24.157 --> 52:27.956
<i>She didn't care if lower Neptune</i>
<i>was buried under a pile of rubble.</i>

52:27.956 --> 52:30.085
<i>She was getting the hell out of Dodge.</i>

52:30.085 --> 52:31.421
‐ What?

52:33.551 --> 52:36.933
VERONICA: <i>My issue with trust,</i>
<i>it's not hardwiring...</i>

52:36.933 --> 52:39.688
NICOLE: Great. Thank you. Bye.
VERONICA: <i>It's experience.</i>

52:39.688 --> 52:40.982
[ hangs up phone ]

52:40.982 --> 52:42.068
‐ You ready?

52:42.068 --> 52:44.280
‐ Let's do it.

52:44.280 --> 52:46.911
VERONICA:
<i>And in my experience,</i>

52:46.911 --> 52:49.082
<i>the people you care about</i>
<i>let you down...</i>

52:51.587 --> 52:53.173
<i>but only if you let them.</i>

52:54.718 --> 52:56.722
<i>[ music playing ]</i>
